WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.832
[SQUEAKING][RUSTLING][CLICKING]

00:00:09.485 --> 00:00:11.110
FRANK SCHILBACH: All
right, so welcome.

00:00:11.110 --> 00:00:14.410
This is lecture 21 of 14.13.

00:00:14.410 --> 00:00:16.660
We're going to talk
about poverty, as seen

00:00:16.660 --> 00:00:20.740
through the lens of psychology.

00:00:20.740 --> 00:00:21.910
What are we going to do?

00:00:21.910 --> 00:00:23.950
I'm going to give you
some broad overview.

00:00:23.950 --> 00:00:27.820
We're going to particularly
talk about this work on scarcity

00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:31.720
by Mani et al., which is
the idea that thinking--

00:00:31.720 --> 00:00:35.020
our thoughts about poverty
captures people's minds, which

00:00:35.020 --> 00:00:38.020
in turn leaves less
capacity in people's minds

00:00:38.020 --> 00:00:39.280
to do other things.

00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:41.200
And then we're going
to talk a little bit

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:46.270
at the end, at least briefly,
about other deprivations

00:00:46.270 --> 00:00:48.900
that poverty entails.

00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:51.070
Some of this is
what I have done.

00:00:51.070 --> 00:00:55.040
Some of this work by others.

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:58.250
So I want to start with
a simple observation that

00:00:58.250 --> 00:01:02.690
is sort of at the heart of
a lot of this literature.

00:01:02.690 --> 00:01:06.932
And the observation is that when
you look around in the world

00:01:06.932 --> 00:01:08.390
and look for
evidence, and when you

00:01:08.390 --> 00:01:11.570
work on poverty-related
issues, you'll

00:01:11.570 --> 00:01:16.700
see or observe quite a few
seemingly suboptimal behaviors

00:01:16.700 --> 00:01:18.020
among the poor.

00:01:18.020 --> 00:01:22.160
This would be things like
lack of investment or taking

00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:24.800
advantage of high return
investment opportunities.

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:27.470
This would be like investment
in fertilizer or health

00:01:27.470 --> 00:01:33.560
investments or machines
or low savings,

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:36.020
in particular some things
like precautionary savings,

00:01:36.020 --> 00:01:39.350
like being ready for shocks,
saving for the future,

00:01:39.350 --> 00:01:41.460
for retirement, and so on.

00:01:41.460 --> 00:01:44.330
At the same time,
sort of high return

00:01:44.330 --> 00:01:47.000
or high interest
rate credit, people

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:49.490
take very high interest loans.

00:01:49.490 --> 00:01:52.920
In part-- what I've shown
you earlier in the class,

00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:55.460
that's particularly
prevalent among the poor.

00:01:55.460 --> 00:01:59.990
There's some evidence of
worse performance of parenting

00:01:59.990 --> 00:02:02.870
among poor parents, including
things like violence

00:02:02.870 --> 00:02:05.810
against children and so on.

00:02:05.810 --> 00:02:11.630
There is some evidence of lower
productivity, punctuality,

00:02:11.630 --> 00:02:15.410
lower medical
adherence for drugs

00:02:15.410 --> 00:02:17.750
that are sort of even very
high stakes drugs that

00:02:17.750 --> 00:02:19.430
are lifesaving.

00:02:19.430 --> 00:02:23.810
There's some evidence of
food and drug consumptions

00:02:23.810 --> 00:02:30.950
in terms of healthy
eating or excessive drug

00:02:30.950 --> 00:02:31.940
use and the like.

00:02:31.940 --> 00:02:35.510
All of those things tend to be
correlated one way or the other

00:02:35.510 --> 00:02:39.890
with different forms
of income or poverty.

00:02:39.890 --> 00:02:44.480
So now you might say, well
that's interesting, but now

00:02:44.480 --> 00:02:46.780
what explains these behaviors?

00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:47.960
How do we think about this?

00:02:47.960 --> 00:02:50.510
What [AUDIO OUT] plausible
explanation kinds

00:02:50.510 --> 00:02:53.000
of autocorrelations.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.920
To be very clear, these
are correlations, not

00:02:56.920 --> 00:02:58.438
causal effects.

00:02:58.438 --> 00:03:00.730
So education could explain
quite a few of those things.

00:03:00.730 --> 00:03:02.910
It could explain
potentially productivity

00:03:02.910 --> 00:03:06.170
and it could explain
potentially parenting

00:03:06.170 --> 00:03:10.690
and it could explain some
form of financial investments.

00:03:10.690 --> 00:03:13.300
It could also explain things
like medical insurance.

00:03:13.300 --> 00:03:20.060
For example, if you look
at in some settings where

00:03:20.060 --> 00:03:24.110
people have not sort
of learned in school

00:03:24.110 --> 00:03:27.277
any basics of medicine or
biology and so on and sort of

00:03:27.277 --> 00:03:29.360
and it's not obvious that
you should take medicine

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:31.580
from a traditional doctor
versus from some healer

00:03:31.580 --> 00:03:33.913
in the village, because how
would you know what's better

00:03:33.913 --> 00:03:34.628
and what's worse.

00:03:34.628 --> 00:03:36.420
And sort of presumably
some of these things

00:03:36.420 --> 00:03:38.820
you would learn in school.

00:03:38.820 --> 00:03:41.210
So one broad
explanatory factor is

00:03:41.210 --> 00:03:43.330
sort of like, [INAUDIBLE]
variables if you want,

00:03:43.330 --> 00:03:46.860
and one of them is
potentially education.

00:03:46.860 --> 00:03:49.710
It's not about omitted variable.

00:03:49.710 --> 00:03:54.900
This is about a treatment
effect of poverty itself.

00:03:54.900 --> 00:03:56.890
And I'm going to be more
specific about that.

00:03:56.890 --> 00:04:00.615
But essentially it's something
about being in poverty itself

00:04:00.615 --> 00:04:01.740
affects people's behaviors.

00:04:01.740 --> 00:04:04.047
So it causes them--

00:04:04.047 --> 00:04:05.880
some of these outcomes,
some of these things

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:06.810
that we've seen here.

00:04:06.810 --> 00:04:09.480
We'll talk about that in detail,
but that's exactly right.

00:04:09.480 --> 00:04:13.260
In some ways, people
would say, even for--

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:15.520
if you take credit for
example, or for some things,

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:17.712
you probably can't explain.

00:04:17.712 --> 00:04:19.170
But for high return
investment, you

00:04:19.170 --> 00:04:20.670
would say, while
there's uncertainty

00:04:20.670 --> 00:04:22.620
and there's a good chance
that there might be losses

00:04:22.620 --> 00:04:24.210
at the end of the
day, and if you're

00:04:24.210 --> 00:04:27.210
really close to
subsistence, you might not

00:04:27.210 --> 00:04:31.290
want to invest in stocks,
because if a bad shock happens,

00:04:31.290 --> 00:04:33.055
that's really bad.

00:04:33.055 --> 00:04:34.430
So I think some
of that is right.

00:04:34.430 --> 00:04:37.625
And punctuality, for
example, could also

00:04:37.625 --> 00:04:38.750
be in some way uncertainty.

00:04:38.750 --> 00:04:40.820
It's like you try to
take a bus to work

00:04:40.820 --> 00:04:42.570
and the bus just
comes every hour,

00:04:42.570 --> 00:04:44.570
and then sometimes it
comes a half an hour early

00:04:44.570 --> 00:04:45.778
and sometimes it comes later.

00:04:45.778 --> 00:04:48.110
And it's really hard to
be actually punctual.

00:04:48.110 --> 00:04:50.840
Could just be some
people are not productive

00:04:50.840 --> 00:04:52.460
and are just bad at doing stuff.

00:04:52.460 --> 00:04:55.340
And therefore, they
become poor and then

00:04:55.340 --> 00:04:57.555
they end up being
poor because of that.

00:04:57.555 --> 00:04:59.180
So that's essentially,
I think, that we

00:04:59.180 --> 00:05:00.472
covered pretty much everything.

00:05:00.472 --> 00:05:03.170
So one is it could be sort of
environmental conditions, which

00:05:03.170 --> 00:05:06.230
is transportation, it's really
hard to get to work on time,

00:05:06.230 --> 00:05:07.970
or have the community
for two hours

00:05:07.970 --> 00:05:10.730
and then you're really tired and
that makes you less productive.

00:05:10.730 --> 00:05:12.440
Things like predatory
lending sort

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:14.630
of tricks you into lending.

00:05:14.630 --> 00:05:17.240
There could some some things
about institutional structures,

00:05:17.240 --> 00:05:20.900
which is to say, I told
you for example at MIT,

00:05:20.900 --> 00:05:23.510
there's a default--

00:05:23.510 --> 00:05:25.340
or at other places,
there's defaults

00:05:25.340 --> 00:05:26.690
for people to save money.

00:05:26.690 --> 00:05:28.880
And there's a default
to get health insurance.

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:31.550
And there's defaults for
all sorts of good behaviors,

00:05:31.550 --> 00:05:36.470
like for vaccinations
and so on and so forth.

00:05:36.470 --> 00:05:38.850
We are sort of essentially
pushed by society,

00:05:38.850 --> 00:05:40.820
by the environmental
conditions that we

00:05:40.820 --> 00:05:44.032
face into doing the right thing
or whatever good behaviors,

00:05:44.032 --> 00:05:45.240
whatever you want to call it.

00:05:45.240 --> 00:05:48.650
And so the poor might just
not have those things.

00:05:48.650 --> 00:05:50.210
So for example,
having a bank account

00:05:50.210 --> 00:05:55.558
might be like if you paid
daily or you can buy by trip.

00:05:55.558 --> 00:05:57.350
The rickshaw drivers
that I was showing you

00:05:57.350 --> 00:05:59.900
earlier in the semester,
they paid trip by trip

00:05:59.900 --> 00:06:02.960
and then they'd pass
by the liquor stores,

00:06:02.960 --> 00:06:05.738
essentially daily, and have
a bunch of cash on hand.

00:06:05.738 --> 00:06:08.280
Well, that's much trickier to
sort of resist sometimes, since

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:11.180
if you were particularly
also prone to physical pain,

00:06:11.180 --> 00:06:13.790
and then sort of to
use alcohol as a way

00:06:13.790 --> 00:06:15.650
to deal with your physical pain.

00:06:15.650 --> 00:06:18.950
As opposed to somebody who paid
monthly and half of the money

00:06:18.950 --> 00:06:22.250
goes into the rent anyway and
then other expenses and so on,

00:06:22.250 --> 00:06:23.993
which is much easier to manage.

00:06:23.993 --> 00:06:25.910
So that's kind of broadly
I would summarize it

00:06:25.910 --> 00:06:28.500
as environmental conditions.

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:31.170
Then there's selection
and omitted variables,

00:06:31.170 --> 00:06:33.480
which is, I think Joseph
has mentioned education,

00:06:33.480 --> 00:06:35.170
which is a very good one.

00:06:35.170 --> 00:06:37.790
There's things
like intelligence,

00:06:37.790 --> 00:06:40.160
talent, effort,
mistakes, and so on.

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:43.850
You might say, well, if you
are more prone-- if you're

00:06:43.850 --> 00:06:46.560
less productive, for example, if
you're prone to making mistakes

00:06:46.560 --> 00:06:48.860
and so on, well
that sort of leads

00:06:48.860 --> 00:06:52.610
to worse outcomes and that
makes you end up being poor.

00:06:52.610 --> 00:06:57.530
And that's really sort of
in some sense, a right wing

00:06:57.530 --> 00:06:59.665
kind of view, that people are--

00:06:59.665 --> 00:07:01.290
they should do whatever
they want to do

00:07:01.290 --> 00:07:04.380
and if the end of being poor,
it's sort of their fault,

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:05.030
and so on.

00:07:05.030 --> 00:07:07.430
That's of course not what
we're going to argue here.

00:07:07.430 --> 00:07:08.600
What we're interested
in-- or what

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:11.225
I'm trying to argue [AUDIO OUT]
show you some evidence off this

00:07:11.225 --> 00:07:15.770
that there's a treatment effect
of poverty itself potentially.

00:07:15.770 --> 00:07:20.420
Which is to say that being poor
itself causes these behaviors.

00:07:20.420 --> 00:07:24.240
And again, I'll show you
the evidence in two ways.

00:07:24.240 --> 00:07:28.190
One is by inducing
thoughts about money,

00:07:28.190 --> 00:07:31.220
essentially thinking about
can you pay school fees,

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:33.860
can pay your rent, can you get
groceries for your children,

00:07:33.860 --> 00:07:36.360
are your children are going to
be hungry tonight, and so on.

00:07:36.360 --> 00:07:38.120
These are all kind of
thoughts that invade

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:40.610
people's minds involuntarily.

00:07:40.610 --> 00:07:44.150
And by doing so, they
capture people's attention.

00:07:44.150 --> 00:07:47.090
And then since attention
overall is limited,

00:07:47.090 --> 00:07:50.660
people have less attention
available for other things.

00:07:50.660 --> 00:07:55.120
That's sort of one broad theory.

00:07:55.120 --> 00:08:00.520
And I'll focus on
that mostly which

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:03.040
people refer to it under
the name of scarcity.

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:06.250
And then there's a bunch
of other aspects of poverty

00:08:06.250 --> 00:08:08.950
as well that might be
competing with people's

00:08:08.950 --> 00:08:12.370
cognitive function, their
attention, that tire them out.

00:08:12.370 --> 00:08:16.840
They're just not sleeping
well, be in pain, being exposed

00:08:16.840 --> 00:08:21.250
to pollution, environmental
pollution, noise pollution,

00:08:21.250 --> 00:08:23.630
and so on, and so forth.

00:08:23.630 --> 00:08:27.045
And so now what's the
underlying idea here?

00:08:27.045 --> 00:08:28.920
Well again, the underlying
idea is that there

00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:31.240
might be what's called--

00:08:31.240 --> 00:08:33.605
people might want to call
it behavioral poverty trap.

00:08:33.605 --> 00:08:34.980
And the broad line
of argument is

00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:37.679
that poverty affects people's
cognition, decision making,

00:08:37.679 --> 00:08:38.909
or productivity.

00:08:38.909 --> 00:08:41.370
These factors in
turn then influence

00:08:41.370 --> 00:08:45.180
people's future poverty,
because if you're not productive

00:08:45.180 --> 00:08:46.680
and you can't save
money and so on,

00:08:46.680 --> 00:08:49.020
you're going to be more
poor in the future.

00:08:49.020 --> 00:08:50.640
And if those things
are going on,

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:54.330
there is essentially some form
of a vicious cycle going on,

00:08:54.330 --> 00:08:57.490
which makes it difficult,
if not impossible,

00:08:57.490 --> 00:08:59.370
for a person to become rich.

00:08:59.370 --> 00:09:02.428
Now notice at the very least,
that will lower mobility.

00:09:02.428 --> 00:09:04.720
Sometimes if you're poor and
you want to become richer,

00:09:04.720 --> 00:09:06.637
you have got to deal
with a bunch of bad stuff

00:09:06.637 --> 00:09:10.260
that happens to you every day.

00:09:10.260 --> 00:09:13.340
But [INAUDIBLE] mobility is low,
[INAUDIBLE] might be actually

00:09:13.340 --> 00:09:13.840
a trap.

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:17.190
It's just next to or actually
impossible to become richer,

00:09:17.190 --> 00:09:21.690
because all these forces are too
strong to overcome for people.

00:09:21.690 --> 00:09:24.610
So today I'm going to talk about
two broad lines of research.

00:09:24.610 --> 00:09:27.480
I'm going to focus mostly
on the first one, which

00:09:27.480 --> 00:09:30.763
is monetary concerns capture
people's cognitive function.

00:09:30.763 --> 00:09:33.180
I'm going to talk a little bit
about other poverty-induced

00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:35.460
deprivation of behaviors
which might have sort

00:09:35.460 --> 00:09:39.180
of similar effects overall.

00:09:39.180 --> 00:09:43.780
So now I want to do a
simple test with you.

00:09:43.780 --> 00:09:47.970
So what I'd like
you to do is to--

00:09:47.970 --> 00:09:49.530
sorry, one second.

00:09:49.530 --> 00:09:52.750
I'm trying to-- give me a sec.

00:09:52.750 --> 00:09:54.418
I'd like you to--

00:09:54.418 --> 00:09:55.210
hold on one second.

00:09:55.210 --> 00:09:56.224
One second.

00:09:59.900 --> 00:10:00.400
All right.

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:00.710
Ready?

00:10:00.710 --> 00:10:01.850
Don't write anything down.

00:10:01.850 --> 00:10:05.660
Just try to remember it and
then try to recall it in a bit.

00:10:05.660 --> 00:10:07.230
I'm going to start reading.

00:10:07.230 --> 00:10:17.880
Bed, rest, dream, doze, snore,
slumber, blanket, snooze, wake,

00:10:17.880 --> 00:10:20.565
nap, awake, tired.

00:10:29.380 --> 00:10:32.950
OK, now please write down as
many words as you remember.

00:11:08.853 --> 00:11:09.520
10 more seconds.

00:11:23.430 --> 00:11:24.830
All right, so done.

00:11:24.830 --> 00:11:27.948
So usually I would have people
raise their hands, which

00:11:27.948 --> 00:11:28.740
is a little tricky.

00:11:28.740 --> 00:11:30.750
But I'm going to just
read you the list of words

00:11:30.750 --> 00:11:31.708
and you can nod to me--

00:11:31.708 --> 00:11:33.060
I can see some of you, at least.

00:11:33.060 --> 00:11:34.518
You can nod and
tell me whether you

00:11:34.518 --> 00:11:40.082
remember the words that I read.

00:11:40.082 --> 00:11:41.040
OK, I'm going to start.

00:11:41.040 --> 00:11:47.160
Bed, rest-- pretty good--

00:11:47.160 --> 00:11:57.460
dream, doze, snore-- no?

00:11:57.460 --> 00:12:15.700
Slumber, sleep, blanket,
snooze, wake, nap, awake, tired.

00:12:19.010 --> 00:12:20.840
So I know this is
making everybody sleepy

00:12:20.840 --> 00:12:22.420
and want to take a nap.

00:12:22.420 --> 00:12:23.350
Me, too.

00:12:23.350 --> 00:12:27.650
So here's the list of words
that I asked you to remember.

00:12:27.650 --> 00:12:30.003
Now one thing
that's kind of nice

00:12:30.003 --> 00:12:33.680
[INAUDIBLE] most people
remembered quite a few things.

00:12:33.680 --> 00:12:35.180
The majority, for
example, remembers

00:12:35.180 --> 00:12:37.320
bed and so on and so forth.

00:12:37.320 --> 00:12:40.100
Now what's quite interesting
about these words is

00:12:40.100 --> 00:12:41.930
that while I remember--

00:12:41.930 --> 00:12:43.550
I put all these
names up here, which

00:12:43.550 --> 00:12:46.550
is-- these are the words
that I actually read.

00:12:46.550 --> 00:12:48.830
Now one word that's actually
missing in this list

00:12:48.830 --> 00:12:51.350
here is sleep.

00:12:51.350 --> 00:12:53.240
And so you sort of--

00:12:53.240 --> 00:12:56.780
I snuck this in here on--

00:12:56.780 --> 00:12:58.700
this is why I had to go back.

00:12:58.700 --> 00:13:00.920
It turns out I actually
didn't read the word sleep,

00:13:00.920 --> 00:13:03.410
but quite a few of you
were nodding happily

00:13:03.410 --> 00:13:05.090
when I asked you about sleep.

00:13:05.090 --> 00:13:09.960
And what's the reason
why you remembered sleep?

00:13:09.960 --> 00:13:13.180
So all of these words is like--

00:13:13.180 --> 00:13:15.640
they all around sleep.

00:13:15.640 --> 00:13:20.360
So it's really like sleep
should have been there.

00:13:20.360 --> 00:13:21.860
It's kind of the
type of thing where

00:13:21.860 --> 00:13:25.250
people would ask you, have you
been to the parity last week,

00:13:25.250 --> 00:13:27.950
where people just assume-- where
essentially all of the friends

00:13:27.950 --> 00:13:29.750
were there-- people just
assume that you were there,

00:13:29.750 --> 00:13:31.610
as well, because you're
supposed to be there.

00:13:31.610 --> 00:13:33.320
It's like sleep is supposed
to be in this list,

00:13:33.320 --> 00:13:34.445
but we didn't put it there.

00:13:34.445 --> 00:13:36.800
And this is what is
called false memory tests.

00:13:36.800 --> 00:13:39.258
And there's quite a bit of work
on actually false memories.

00:13:39.258 --> 00:13:41.420
And people's minds
essentially make up things.

00:13:41.420 --> 00:13:43.130
In particular, stuff
that's sort of--

00:13:43.130 --> 00:13:46.670
or where you have all
situations that you think

00:13:46.670 --> 00:13:47.960
that should be the case.

00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:52.730
You can do the same with man
and other lists and so on.

00:13:52.730 --> 00:13:56.330
And now psychologists
have been doing studies

00:13:56.330 --> 00:13:57.710
for the rich and the poor.

